    <h2><span style="color: #004b87;">Background</span></h2>
    <h3>What is LiDAR?</h3>
    <p>LiDAR stands for <strong>Light Detection and Ranging</strong>. A LiDAR sensor measures distance by sending out laser light and measuring the reflected signal. The RPLidar A1 spins continuously, allowing it to measure distances around the robot in a full 360-degree circle.</p>
    <p>For this lab, you do not need to build a map or understand every detail of how the LiDAR works internally. You only need to use the distance measurements to answer one question:</p>
    <div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #004B87; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <p style="margin: 0; font-style: italic; color: #555555;"><strong>Question:</strong> Is there something too close in front of the robot?</p>
    </div>
    <h3>The LaserScan Message</h3>
    <p>In ROS2, the LiDAR data is published as a <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">sensor_msgs/msg/LaserScan</code> message on the <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/scan</code> topic.</p>
    <p>The most important part of this message is the <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">ranges</code> array. This array contains many distance measurements around the robot. For this lab, we will treat the scan as if it contains approximately 360 values, where each index corresponds to a direction around the robot.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Index 0:</strong> directly in front of the robot</li>
        <li><strong>Index 90:</strong> directly to the left of the robot</li>
        <li><strong>Index 180:</strong> directly behind the robot</li>
        <li><strong>Index 270:</strong> directly to the right of the robot</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Each value in the array is a distance measurement in meters. A smaller number means an object is closer to the robot.</p>
    <h3>Only Looking at the Front Arc</h3>
    <p>The LiDAR can see all around the robot, but the robot does not need to react to every object around it. If there is a wall behind the robot, the robot should not stop driving forward. For obstacle avoidance, we only care about objects in the direction the robot is trying to move.</p>
    <p>To do this, we only examine a small region in front of the robot. This region is called the <strong>front arc</strong>.</p>
    <p>Because the scan wraps around from 359 degrees back to 0 degrees, the front arc is split across the beginning and end of the array:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">msg.ranges[0:20]</code> looks slightly to the left of straight ahead.</li>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">msg.ranges[340:360]</code> looks slightly to the right of straight ahead.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These two slices are combined so the robot can check only the area directly in front of itself.</p>
    <h3>Filtering Bad Sensor Data</h3>
    <p>Real sensors are not perfect. Sometimes the LiDAR may return values that should not be used for decision making. For example, it may report <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">0.0</code>, <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">inf</code>, or another invalid value when the sensor does not receive a useful reflection.</p>
    <p>If invalid values are not filtered out, the robot may think there is an obstacle directly in front of it even when the path is clear. This can cause the robot to stop, spin, or stutter in open space.</p>
    <h3>Reactive Control</h3>
    <p>This lab uses a simple control strategy called <strong>reactive control</strong>. A reactive robot does not build a map or plan a complete path. Instead, it reacts directly to its current sensor readings.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Sense:</strong> Read the latest LiDAR scan.</li>
        <li><strong>Think:</strong> Check whether the closest object in front of the robot is too close.</li>
        <li><strong>Act:</strong> Drive forward if the path is clear. Turn in place if an obstacle is detected.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is not an advanced navigation system, but it is an important first step toward autonomous robotics.</p>
    <h3>Overview of the Obstacle Avoidance Node</h3>
    <p>The course package already includes an incomplete node named <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">obstacle_avoidance_node.py</code>. This file is part of the <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">romi_base</code> package.</p>
    <p>This node has three main jobs:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Subscribe to the LiDAR scan topic, <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/scan</code>.</li>
        <li>Decide whether the robot should drive forward or turn.</li>
        <li>Publish velocity commands to <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/cmd_vel</code>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The node already contains the basic ROS2 structure. You do not need to create a new file from scratch. Your job is to complete the missing logic inside the LiDAR callback function.</p>
    <div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #004B87; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Important:</strong> A callback function is a function that automatically runs when new data arrives. In this lab, the LiDAR callback runs every time a new <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/scan</code> message is received.</p>
    </div>
