    <h2><span style="color: #004b87;">Procedure</span></h2>
    <h3>1. Open the Code Workspace</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Boot your laptop and connect to your Romi network.</li>
        <li>Launch VS Code.</li>
        <li>Using the WSL extension, open your ROS2 workspace.</li>
        <li>Locate the obstacle avoidance node at:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">~/ros2_ws/src/ROMI-ROS2/romi_base/romi_base/obstacle_avoidance_node.py</pre>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <h3>2. Inspect the Existing Node</h3>
    <p>Before writing code, read through the file and identify the major parts of the node.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">self.publisher</code> is used to send velocity commands to <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/cmd_vel</code>.</li>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">self.subscription</code> is used to receive LiDAR data from <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">/scan</code>.</li>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">forward_speed</code> controls how fast the robot drives forward.</li>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">turning_speed</code> controls how fast the robot rotates when avoiding an obstacle.</li>
        <li><code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">safe_dist</code> controls how close an object is allowed to be before the robot reacts.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These parameters allow the robot behavior to be adjusted without changing the main structure of the program.</p>
    <h3>3. Complete the LiDAR Callback</h3>
    <p>Navigate to the <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">lidar_callback()</code> function. This is where you will complete the obstacle avoidance logic.</p>
    <p>Your code should perform the following steps:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Slice the front arc.</strong><br />Create two lists from the scan data:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">front_left = msg.ranges[0:20]
front_right = msg.ranges[340:360]</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Combine the two lists.</strong><br />These two slices represent the area directly in front of the robot.</li>
        <li><strong>Filter invalid measurements.</strong><br />Remove values that are not useful for obstacle detection. At minimum, remove values that are too small to be real measurements.</li>
        <li><strong>Check whether valid data exists.</strong><br />If there are no valid measurements, the function should return without commanding motion.</li>
        <li><strong>Find the closest object.</strong><br />Use <code style="font-family: monospace; color: #273540;">min()</code> to find the closest valid distance in the front arc.</li>
        <li><strong>Compare the closest object to the safety threshold.</strong><br />Use:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">safe_threshold = self.get_parameter('safe_dist').value</pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Create and publish a Twist command.</strong><br />If the closest object is too close, command the robot to turn. Otherwise, command the robot to drive forward.</li>
    </ol>
    <div style="background-color: #f8f9fa; border-left: 4px solid #004B87; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 4px;">
        <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Important:</strong> Do not make the robot turn because it sees something behind it or beside it. Only the front arc should be used for this lab.</p>
    </div>
    <h3>4. Sync and Rebuild the Project</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Save your file modifications in VS Code.</li>
        <li>In your local WSL terminal, navigate to the repository:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">cd ~/ros2_ws/src/ROMI-ROS2</pre>
        </li>
        <li>Sync the updated project to the Raspberry Pi using the same sync script used in previous labs:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">./scripts/sync_to_pi.sh</pre>
        </li>
        <li>SSH into the Raspberry Pi:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">ssh student@192.168.4.1</pre>
        </li>
        <li>On the Raspberry Pi, rebuild and source the workspace:
            <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build --packages-select romi_base
source install/setup.bash</pre>
        </li>
    </ol>
    <h3>5. Launch the Robot Stack</h3>
    <p>This lab requires the robot base controller, LiDAR driver, and obstacle avoidance node to run at the same time.</p>
    <p>Use separate SSH terminals connected to the Raspberry Pi.</p>
    <p><strong>Terminal 1 &mdash; LiDAR Driver</strong></p>
    <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">ros2 launch rplidar_ros rplidar_a1_launch.py</pre>
    <p><strong>Terminal 2 &mdash; Romi Core Stack</strong></p>
    <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">ros2 launch romi_base romi_core.launch.py</pre>
    <p><strong>Terminal 3 &mdash; Obstacle Avoidance Node</strong></p>
    <pre style="background-color: #1e1e1e; color: #ffffff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: monospace; overflow-x: auto; margin-top: 10px;">ros2 run romi_base obstacle_avoidance_node</pre>
    <p>Once all nodes are running, place the robot on the floor in an open area with enough space to move safely.</p>
    <div style="background-color: #fcf8e3; border-left: 4px solid #f0ad4e; padding: 15px; margin: 20px 0; border-radius: 4px; color: #8a6d3b;">
        <p style="margin: 0;"><strong>Safety:</strong> Be ready to pick up the robot or stop the program if it drives toward a person, table leg, wall, or cable. This is a simple reactive controller and it will not behave perfectly in every situation.</p>
    </div>
    <h3>6. Test the Behavior</h3>
    <p>Test the robot in three stages.</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Open space test:</strong> Place the robot in open space. It should drive forward smoothly.</li>
        <li><strong>Obstacle test:</strong> Place a solid object in front of the robot within the safety distance. The robot should stop and turn.</li>
        <li><strong>Recovery test:</strong> Allow the robot to turn until the front arc is clear. It should automatically resume driving forward.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>If the robot constantly spins in open space, check your filtering logic. If the robot drives into obstacles, check which part of the LiDAR scan is being used as the front arc.</p>
